<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-924-722  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 924 722.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Nov 27 1989 v8 n24 p39(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical disk mobilizes Army for the future.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hosinski, Joan M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical DisksUnited States. ArmyPersonnel ManagementRecords ManagementInformation SystemsRequest for Proposals.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Optical Disk Mobilizes Army for the FutureandM;A key element in the Army's Personnel Electronics Record Management Systemwill be optical-disk imagery, an Army general said this month.andM;Release of the request for proposals for the system has been delayed untilDec. 15.andP;  &quot;We may not make it [then], but damn it, it won't be because wedidn't try,&quot; said Brig.andP;  Gen.andP;  Jack Pellicci, commander of the Army'sPersonnel Information Command in Alexandra, Va.andM;The Army has created its Vision 21 program for information systemsdevelopment, which will lay the groundwork for moving systems into the 21stcentury, Pellicci said.andM;Emphasis is on equipping soldiers rather than on manning equipment, Pelliccisaid, adding that troop deployment procedures need to improve.andM;&quot;All the great machines will not be worth a hoot&quot; if the Army cannot get itstroops deployed, he said at the seminar in Bethesda, Md., sponsored by WangLaboratories Inc. and the Associated Information Managers ImplementingOptical-Disk Imaging Systems.andM;Optical disks will store millions of records and images at personnel recordscenters around the world, Pellicci said.andP;  Data includes medical and financialrecords and images, and National Guard, Army Reserve and active forceinformation.andM;When a division must mobilize it must carry with it all of its records.andP;  Inpaper form, those records weigh 23,000 pounds and fill a tractor-trailer,Pellicci said.andM;But in an optical format, those records would weigh 35 pounds and fit in asmall car.andM;The Army's goal is to create the future, not predict it, Pellicci said.andP;  Onestrategy is to try to understand and work in tandem with sophisticated endusers.andM;The system should be flexible, affordable, reliable and simple.andP;  Pilotprojects can help get the system off the ground.andP;  &quot;I can't sit back and wait&quot;for architectures and other systems to be put in place, Pellicci said.andM;Incremental development of the system also is necessary.andP;  &quot;We've learned fromweapons system work that the ones that failed primarily have every bell andwhistle, and requirements were never frozen,&quot; Pellicci said.andP;  &quot;Just get thesystem out.andP;  It may not be everything you want, but it will be a heck of alot better than what you have now.&quot;andM;System components need to be developed and evaluated with the target audiencein mind Pellicci said.andP;  &quot;We've seen some real horror shows&quot; when this advicehas not been followed, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>